blocks.name: uzmptshftfval
blocks.content: When ` F ` is a maps-to function on some set of upper integers ` Z ` that returns a set ` B ` , ` ( F shift N ) ` is another maps-to function on the shifted set of upper integers ` W ` . (Contributed by Steve Rodriguez, 22-Apr-2020.)
blocks.origin:
thm uzmptshftfval(setvar s0, setvar s1, class c0, class c1, class c2, class c3, class c4, class c5, class c6, wff w0) {
  |- wi(w0, wceq(co(c0, cshi, c1), cmpt(s0, c2, c3)))
  -| wceq(c0, cmpt(s1, c4, c5))
  -| wcel(c5, universe)
  -| wi(wceq(cv(s1), co(cv(s0), cmin, c1)), wceq(c5, c3))
  -| wceq(c4, cfv(cuz, c6))
  -| wceq(c2, cfv(cuz, co(c6, caddc, c1)))
  -| wi(w0, wcel(c6, cz))
  -| wi(w0, wcel(c1, cz))
  -| diffss(s0, s1)
  -| diffsc(s0, c0)
  -| diffsc(s0, c1)
  -| diffsc(s0, c2)
  -| diffsc(s0, c4)
  -| diffsc(s0, c6)
  -| diffsc(s1, c1)
  -| diffsc(s1, c3)
  -| diffsc(s1, c4)
  -| diffsw(s0, w0)
} = {
  eqtrd(co(c0, cshi, c1), cmpt(s0, c2, c3), cmpt(s0, c2, cfv(co(c0, cshi, c1), cv(s0))), w0)
  sylib(w0, wceq(co(c0, cshi, c1), cmpt(s0, c2, cfv(co(c0, cshi, c1), cv(s0)))), wfn(co(c0, cshi, c1), c2))
  mpbid(w0, wfn(co(c0, cshi, c1), c2), wfn(co(c0, cshi, c1), crab(s0, cc, wcel(co(cv(s0), cmin, c1), c4))))
  sylancr(w0, wfn(co(c0, cshi, c1), crab(s0, cc, wcel(co(cv(s0), cmin, c1), c4))), wfn(c0, c4), wcel(c1, cc))
  fnmpti(s1, c0, c4, c5)
  shftfn(s0, c0, c4, c1)
  fneq2d(co(c0, cshi, c1), crab(s0, cc, wcel(co(cv(s0), cmin, c1), c4)), c2, w0)
  3eqtr4g(crab(s0, cc, wcel(co(cv(s0), cmin, c1), c4)), c2, crab(s0, cc, wcel(co(cv(s0), cmin, c1), cfv(cuz, c6))), cfv(cuz, co(c6, caddc, c1)), w0)
  syl2anc(w0, wceq(crab(s0, cc, wcel(co(cv(s0), cmin, c1), cfv(cuz, c6))), cfv(cuz, co(c6, caddc, c1))), wcel(c1, cz), wcel(c6, cz))
  shftuz(s0, c1, c6)
  rabbii(s0, cc, wcel(co(cv(s0), cmin, c1), c4), wcel(co(cv(s0), cmin, c1), cfv(cuz, c6)))
  eleq2i(co(cv(s0), cmin, c1), c4, cfv(cuz, c6))
  dffn5(s0, co(c0, cshi, c1), c2)
  mpteq2dva(s0, c2, cfv(co(c0, cshi, c1), cv(s0)), c3, w0)
  eqtrd(cfv(co(c0, cshi, c1), cv(s0)), c3, cfv(c0, co(cv(s0), cmin, c1)), wa(w0, wcel(cv(s0), c2)))
  syl2an(w0, wcel(cv(s0), c2), wceq(cfv(co(c0, cshi, c1), cv(s0)), cfv(c0, co(cv(s0), cmin, c1))), wcel(c1, cc), wcel(cv(s0), cc))
  zcnd(c1, w0)
  sseli(cv(s0), c2, cc)
  sstri(c2, cc, cz)
  eqsstri(c2, cz, cfv(cuz, co(c6, caddc, c1)))
  uzssz(co(c6, caddc, c1))
  zsscn()
  shftval(c1, cv(s0), c0)
  eqeltri(c0, universe, cmpt(s1, c4, c5))
  mptex(s1, c4, c5)
  fvexi(c4, cuz, c6)
  syl(wa(w0, wcel(cv(s0), c2)), wceq(cfv(c0, co(cv(s0), cmin, c1)), c3), wcel(co(cv(s0), cmin, c1), c4))
  syl6eleqr(co(cv(s0), cmin, c1), c4, cfv(cuz, c6), wa(w0, wcel(cv(s0), c2)))
  sylan2b(w0, wcel(cv(s0), c2), wcel(co(cv(s0), cmin, c1), cfv(cuz, c6)), wcel(cv(s0), cfv(cuz, co(c6, caddc, c1))))
  eleq2i(cv(s0), c2, cfv(cuz, co(c6, caddc, c1)))
  sylan(w0, wcel(cv(s0), cfv(cuz, co(c6, caddc, c1))), wcel(co(cv(s0), cmin, c1), cfv(cuz, c6)), wa(wcel(c6, cz), wcel(c1, cz)))
  jca(w0, wcel(c6, cz), wcel(c1, cz))
  3expa(wcel(c6, cz), wcel(c1, cz), wcel(cv(s0), cfv(cuz, co(c6, caddc, c1))), wcel(co(cv(s0), cmin, c1), cfv(cuz, c6)))
  eluzsub(c6, c1, cv(s0))
  fvmpt3i(s1, co(cv(s0), cmin, c1), c4, c0, c3, c5)
  diff.co.s(s0, c0, cshi, c1)
  diff.cshi.s(s0)
  diff.co.s(s1, cv(s0), cmin, c1)
  diff.cv.s(s1, s0)
  diffss.ex(s1, s0)
  diff.cmin.s(s1)
}

thm uzmptshftfval(setvar s0, setvar s1, class c0, class c1, class c2, class c3, class c4, class c5, class c6, wff w0) {
  ‚ä¢ (w0 ‚Üí(c0[shift]c1)=(s0 ‚àà c2 ‚Ü¶ c3))
  ‚ä£ c0 =(s1 ‚àà c4 ‚Ü¶ c5)
  ‚ä£ c5 ‚àà ùïå
  ‚ä£ (s1 =(s0[-]c1)‚Üí c5 = c3)
  ‚ä£ c4 =(‚Ñ§‚â• ` c6)
  ‚ä£ c2 =(‚Ñ§‚â• `(c6[+]c1))
  ‚ä£ (w0 ‚Üí c6 ‚àà ‚Ñ§)
  ‚ä£ (w0 ‚Üí c1 ‚àà ‚Ñ§)
  ‚ä£ d(s0, s1)
  ‚ä£ d(s0, c0)
  ‚ä£ d(s0, c1)
  ‚ä£ d(s0, c2)
  ‚ä£ d(s0, c4)
  ‚ä£ d(s0, c6)
  ‚ä£ d(s1, c1)
  ‚ä£ d(s1, c3)
  ‚ä£ d(s1, c4)
  ‚ä£ d(s0, w0)
} = {
  eqtrd((c0[shift]c1), (s0 ‚àà c2 ‚Ü¶ c3), (s0 ‚àà c2 ‚Ü¶((c0[shift]c1)` s0)), w0)
  sylib(w0, (c0[shift]c1)=(s0 ‚àà c2 ‚Ü¶((c0[shift]c1)` s0)), (c0[shift]c1)[Fn]c2)
  mpbid(w0, (c0[shift]c1)[Fn]c2, (c0[shift]c1)[Fn]{ s0 ‚àà ‚ÑÇ |(s0[-]c1)‚àà c4 })
  sylancr(w0, (c0[shift]c1)[Fn]{ s0 ‚àà ‚ÑÇ |(s0[-]c1)‚àà c4 }, c0[Fn]c4, c1 ‚àà ‚ÑÇ)
  fnmpti(s1, c0, c4, c5)
  shftfn(s0, c0, c4, c1)
  fneq2d((c0[shift]c1), { s0 ‚àà ‚ÑÇ |(s0[-]c1)‚àà c4 }, c2, w0)
  3eqtr4g({ s0 ‚àà ‚ÑÇ |(s0[-]c1)‚àà c4 }, c2, { s0 ‚àà ‚ÑÇ |(s0[-]c1)‚àà(‚Ñ§‚â• ` c6)}, (‚Ñ§‚â• `(c6[+]c1)), w0)
  syl2anc(w0, { s0 ‚àà ‚ÑÇ |(s0[-]c1)‚àà(‚Ñ§‚â• ` c6)} =(‚Ñ§‚â• `(c6[+]c1)), c1 ‚àà ‚Ñ§, c6 ‚àà ‚Ñ§)
  shftuz(s0, c1, c6)
  rabbii(s0, cc, (s0[-]c1)‚àà c4, (s0[-]c1)‚àà(‚Ñ§‚â• ` c6))
  eleq2i((s0[-]c1), c4, (‚Ñ§‚â• ` c6))
  dffn5(s0, (c0[shift]c1), c2)
  mpteq2dva(s0, c2, ((c0[shift]c1)` s0), c3, w0)
  eqtrd(((c0[shift]c1)` s0), c3, (c0 `(s0[-]c1)), (w0 ‚àß s0 ‚àà c2))
  syl2an(w0, s0 ‚àà c2, ((c0[shift]c1)` s0)=(c0 `(s0[-]c1)), c1 ‚àà ‚ÑÇ, s0 ‚àà ‚ÑÇ)
  zcnd(c1, w0)
  sseli(s0, c2, cc)
  sstri(c2, cc, cz)
  eqsstri(c2, cz, (‚Ñ§‚â• `(c6[+]c1)))
  uzssz((c6[+]c1))
  zsscn()
  shftval(c1, s0, c0)
  eqeltri(c0, universe, (s1 ‚àà c4 ‚Ü¶ c5))
  mptex(s1, c4, c5)
  fvexi(c4, cuz, c6)
  syl((w0 ‚àß s0 ‚àà c2), (c0 `(s0[-]c1))= c3, (s0[-]c1)‚àà c4)
  syl6eleqr((s0[-]c1), c4, (‚Ñ§‚â• ` c6), (w0 ‚àß s0 ‚àà c2))
  sylan2b(w0, s0 ‚àà c2, (s0[-]c1)‚àà(‚Ñ§‚â• ` c6), s0 ‚àà(‚Ñ§‚â• `(c6[+]c1)))
  eleq2i(s0, c2, (‚Ñ§‚â• `(c6[+]c1)))
  sylan(w0, s0 ‚àà(‚Ñ§‚â• `(c6[+]c1)), (s0[-]c1)‚àà(‚Ñ§‚â• ` c6), (c6 ‚àà ‚Ñ§ ‚àß c1 ‚àà ‚Ñ§))
  jca(w0, c6 ‚àà ‚Ñ§, c1 ‚àà ‚Ñ§)
  3expa(c6 ‚àà ‚Ñ§, c1 ‚àà ‚Ñ§, s0 ‚àà(‚Ñ§‚â• `(c6[+]c1)), (s0[-]c1)‚àà(‚Ñ§‚â• ` c6))
  eluzsub(c6, c1, s0)
  fvmpt3i(s1, (s0[-]c1), c4, c0, c3, c5)
  diff.co.s(s0, c0, cshi, c1)
  diff.cshi.s(s0)
  diff.co.s(s1, s0, cmin, c1)
  diff.cv.s(s1, s0)
  diffss.ex(s1, s0)
  diff.cmin.s(s1)
}

blocks.name: dvradcnv2
blocks.content: The radius of convergence of the (formal) derivative ` H ` of the power series ` G ` is (at least) as large as the radius of convergence of ` G ` . This version of ~ dvradcnv uses a shifted version of ` H ` to match the sum form of ` ( CC _D F ) ` in ~ pserdv2 (and shows how to use ~ uzmptshftfval to shift a maps-to function on a set of upper integers). (Contributed by Steve Rodriguez, 22-Apr-2020.)
blocks.origin:

blocks.name: binomcxplemnn0
blocks.content: Lemma for ~ binomcxp . When ` C ` is a nonnegative integer, the binomial's finite sum value by the standard binomial theorem ~ binom equals this generalized infinite sum: the generalized binomial coefficient and exponentiation operators give exactly the same values in the standard index set ` ( 0 ... C ) ` , and when the index set is widened beyond ` C ` the additional values are just zeroes. (Contributed by Steve Rodriguez, 22-Apr-2020.)

blocks.name: binomcxplemrat
blocks.content: Lemma for ~ binomcxp . As ` k ` increases, this ratio's absolute value converges to one. Part of equation "Since continuity of the absolute value..." in the Wikibooks proof (proven for the inverse ratio, which we later show is no problem). (Contributed by Steve Rodriguez, 22-Apr-2020.)

blocks.content: Lemma for ~ binomcxp . ~ binomcxplemrat implies that when ` C ` is not a nonnegative integer, the absolute value of the ratio ` ( ( F `` ( k + 1 ) ) / ( F `` k ) ) ` converges to one. The rest of equation "Since continuity of the absolute value..." in the Wikibooks proof. (Contributed by Steve Rodriguez, 22-Apr-2020.)

blocks.name: binomcxplemdvbinom
blocks.content: Lemma for ~ binomcxp . By the power and chain rules, calculate the derivative of ` ( ( 1 + b ) ^c -u C ) ` , with respect to ` b ` in the disk of convergence ` D ` . We later multiply the derivative in the later ~ binomcxplemdvsum by this derivative to show that ` ( ( 1 + b ) ^c C ) ` (with a non-negated ` C ` ) and the later sum, since both at ` b = 0 ` equal one, are the same. (Contributed by Steve Rodriguez, 22-Apr-2020.)

blocks.name: binomcxplemcvg
blocks.content: Lemma for ~ binomcxp . The sum in ~ binomcxplemnn0 and its derivative (see the next theorem, ~ binomcxplemdvsum ) converge, as long as their base ` J ` is within the disk of convergence. Part of remark "This convergence allows us to apply term-by-term differentiation..." in the Wikibooks proof. (Contributed by Steve Rodriguez, 22-Apr-2020.)

blocks.name: binomcxplemnotnn0
blocks.content: Lemma for ~ binomcxp . When ` C ` is not a nonnegative integer, the generalized sum in ~ binomcxplemnn0 —which we will call ` P ` —is a convergent power series: its base ` b ` is always of smaller absolute value than the radius of convergence. ~ pserdv2 gives the derivative of ` P ` , which by ~ dvradcnv also converges in that radius. When ` A ` is fixed at one, ` ( A + b ) ` times that derivative equals ` ( C x. P ) ` and fraction ` ( P / ( ( A + b ) ^c C ) ) ` is always defined with derivative zero, so the fraction is a constant—specifically one, because ` ( ( 1 + 0 ) ^c C ) = 1 ` . Thus ` ( ( 1 + b ) ^c C ) = ( P `` b ) ` . Finally, let ` b ` be ` ( B / A ) ` , and multiply both the binomial ` ( ( 1 + ( B / A ) ) ^c C ) ` and the sum ` ( P `` ( B / A ) ) ` by ` ( A ^c C ) ` to get the result. (Contributed by Steve Rodriguez, 22-Apr-2020.)

blocks.name: binomcxp
blocks.content: Generalize the binomial theorem ~ binom to positive real summand ` A ` , real summand ` B ` , and complex exponent ` C ` . Proof in ~ https://en.wikibooks.org/wiki/Advanced_Calculus ; see also ~ https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binomial_series , ~ https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binomial_theorem (sections "Newton's generalized binomial theorem" and "Future generalizations"), and proof "General Binomial Theorem" in ~ https://proofwiki.org/wiki/Binomial_Theorem . (Contributed by Steve Rodriguez, 22-Apr-2020.)
blocks.origin:
